(502, 1, '2013-04-11 18:16:16', '2013-04-11 18:16:16', '<h2><span style="color: #000000;">It’s the question we’re all asking. Will you lead?</span></h2>\r\nEvery year, students have the opportunity to participate in a process that is amazing. Students have a chance to serve as members of the Executive Cabinet of the Student Government Association. As the highest elected body on campus, the Student Government Association has the duty of articulating the student voice to the administration and beyond. The cabinet of 17 people represent the entire student body at UMW and then –under the direction of the SGA President– work to find solutions for common problems on campus. The SGA strives to work together to turn UMW Problems into solutions. Each member of the cabinet has a different job that they do that benefits the student body in a different way. The question you have to ask yourself is… <strong>will you lead?</strong>\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>How do you run to serve UMW?</strong></span></h2>\r\nTo run for office you <strong><em>must</em> </strong>attend an election workshop or contact the SGA by March 11th, 2013 by midnight (sga@mail.umw.edu) to become nominated. Election workshops are Monday March 11, 2013 and Tuesday March 12, 2013 at 5PM in the Underground. Nominations will be Wednesday March 13, 2013 in the James Farmer Lecture Hall (Monroe 116) at 4:30 PM. The results of the Executive Cabinet Elections will be announced Wednesday March 20, 2013. For more questions, please contact the SGA.<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong> The Office of the President</strong></span></h2>\r\nThe President of the SGA is the official voice of the SGA and the Student Body. The president is responsible for the efficient operation of the SGA and reports to President Hurley. The SGA President also presents a report to the Board of Visitors and advocated for all of the students needs. and preferences. The Student Body President is responsible for the efficient operation of the SGA. The President appoints all students to committees on campus. The SGA President has the power to fill appointed positions which are as follows: The Executive Coordinator, the Communications Director, the Director of Community Outreach, the Technology Coordinator, the Treasurer and the Secretary.\r\n\r\n<em>To become SGA President, a student must be enrolled at the University of Mary Washington at the time of nominations, be in good academic standing (2.2 or above) and no pending judicial charges.</em>\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>The Office of the Vice President</strong></span></h2>\r\nThe Vice President is the official voice of the Senate and takes over if the President is unable to fulfill their duties. The Vice President is in charge of the daily operation of the Senate and will appoint all the committee chairpersons at the start of each new academic year. The Vice President bring the Executive Cabinet all senate motions for their consideration.\r\n\r\n<em>To become SGA Vice President, a student must be enrolled at the University of Mary Washington at the time of nominations, be in good academic standing (2.2 or above) and no pending judicial charges. Furthermore, you must have served one semester in the Senate, including the semester in which you are running for election.</em>\r\n<h3><strong><span style="color: #000000;">The Honor Council President</span>\r\n</strong></h3>\r\nThe Honor Council President represents the SGA on all issues of Honor while leading the Honor Council during hearings. The Honor Council President leads the judicial branch of the SGA ensuring every student is aware of Honor and how it impact their lives at UMW.\r\n\r\n<em>To become Honor Council President, a student must be enrolled at the University of Mary Washington at the time of nominations, be in good academic standing (2.2 or above) and no pending judicial charges. </em>\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>The Office Legislative Action Committee Chairperson</strong></span></h2>\r\nThe LAC Chair is responsible for dealing with all politics that affect the university. The LAC Chair works with the local, state and federal government on all issues that benefit or affect Mary Washington. The LAC Chair works with the SGA to plan Lobby Day, Constitution Day and works to advice the SGA on all issues that are political in nature.\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>The Office of the Commuting Student Association President</strong></span></h2>\r\nThe CSA President is responsible for representing commuter students to SGA, all University Offices and the Fredericksburg Community. The CSA President will work to improve life for commuter students at Mary Washington though student life and other activities.\r\n\r\n<em>To be the CSA President, the Student must be a commuter.</em>\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>The Association of Residence Halls President</strong></span></h2>\r\nThe ARH President represents all issues of residence life to the SGA. They’ve helped work on projects like Party Smart this year and help students work with Hall Councils to achieve various goals in their Residence Halls.\r\n<h3><strong><span style="color: #000000;">The Academic Affairs Committee Chairperson</span>\r\n</strong></h3>\r\nThe AAC Chair works to represent students to our amazing faculty. The Chair works with the faculty often to articulate what students are thinking and then in turn return those concerns back to the SGA. In the upcoming year, the AAC Chair will work to ensure student voices are heard in the University Faculty Governance Structure.\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>The Office of the Diversity and Unity Coordinating Committee Executive Chairperson</strong></span></h2>\r\nThe DUCC Executive Chairperson is responsible for running all DUCC meetings and works to correspond with the administration and faculty in regards to programming of DUCC initiatives. The DUCC Executive Chairperson will appoint their own Vice President within two weeks of being elected.\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>The Office of the Inter-Club Association President</strong></span></h2>\r\nThe ICA President organizes the Club Presidents meeting each month for the purpose of distributing information that concern the students involved. The ICA President works with the Executive Cabinet to admit new clubs into ICA.\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Judicial Review Board President</strong></span></h2>\r\nThe JRB is also a branch of the Judicial side of the SGA and is responsible for fair hearings for students who violate the code of conduct.', 'Elections', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '354-revision-3', '', '', '2013-04-11 18:16:16', '2013-04-11 18:16:16', '', 354, 'http://rosemary.umw.edu/~mdunlap/umwsga/wordpress/?p=502', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
